  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Gender Action Learning System (GALS) was developed under ON&#x92;s WEMAN programme since 2008 with Linda Mayoux and partners. Since 2009 IFAD has been promoting the use of GALS and other innovative household methodologies (HHM) as a mechanism to achieve asignificant and sustainable reduction in rural poverty. GALS and the &quot;Household Mentoring approach&quot; developed as part of the Agricultural Support Programme (ASP) supported by Swedish Sida in Zambia are among the two most comprehensive methodologies promoted by IFAD.

H HM position poor female and male smallholder farmers as drivers of their own development rather than recipients of aid or victims. It enables them to identify and address obstacles in their environment, change gender relations in the household and community, negotiate better prices for their products or better service delivery, and strengthen their asset base1. HHM have been successfully applied in a number of countries and can effectively be integrated into agricultural extension, ruralfinance and value chain development. They increase the pro-poor impact of such economic interventions and can contribute significantly to IFAD&#xB4;s goal of helping 80 millionpeople out of poverty.

For this project a consortium was formed with local CSOsinRwanda, Burundi and DRC to promote sharing of experiences between three countries, capitalise on the opportunities for linking with IFAD programmes in these countries and to bring in more practitioners from Francophone West Africa. The selection of thesethree countries was based on the demand to provide materials in French and to have locations where participants can learn from HMM in practice. The experience and expertise built up with partners and their community groups in Rwanda will be beneficialforthe other two countries but also for IFAD staff from other Francophone countries.

Unrest in Burundi in April before the elections urged the team to postpone the start of the project in Burundi. The inauguration of president of Burundi Nkrunziza inAugust 2015 for a third term created further unrest and political instability, concentrated in Bujumbura. Despite some continuing violent incidents in specific sites, Oxfam assessed the situation sufficiently safe to start implementation in December 2015with a pre-inception meeting, followed by an official inception workshop in February 2016.</narrative>
  </description>
  <participating-org role="4" type="21">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">ACORD</narrative>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Agency for Co-operation and Research in Development (ACORD) was established in 1976 as a consortium of international non-governmental organisations, with the purpose of collectively responding to emergency situations in some of Africa#s poorest, mostcrisis prone and marginalised areas. Over the years, the work developed further into relief, rehabilitation, long-term programming, research and capacity building. ACORD mainly works in African regions where local NGO structures were still weak or absent.This was the anglethat led ACORD to start work in Burundi in the early 1990s.
Oxfam Novib started supporting ACORD in Burundi in 1994, and has continued to support ACORD#s programs over the years. ACORD#s vision, mission and goals are very much in linewith Oxfam Novib#s aims. In the past twenty years ACORD has proven to be capable of successfully realising its mission, especially in African regions characterised by instability. ACORD works with the local people in the most remote and dangerous areas of Burundi, with refugees and displaced people.
Over the past years, Oxfam Novib has through ACORD been able positively to change the situation for many poor and marginalised people in Africa.</narrative>
